#compdef uro
# =============================================================================
# uro — Simone Margaritelli (@evilsocket)'s "GNU/Linux monitoring and
#       profiling tool focused on single processes."  uro (the binary
#       name for the `uroboros` package, named after the
#       OUROBOROS — the ancient mythological serpent eating its own
#       tail, symbolizing the process-introspection loop) is a TUI
#       process-monitor that displays, for a single PID, in real time:
#         - CPU usage breakdown (user / system / nice / iowait)
#         - Memory usage (RSS / VSZ / shared / heap / stack)
#         - I/O statistics (read bytes / write bytes / open file
#                            descriptors)
#         - Threads (count, per-thread CPU%, per-thread state)
#         - Network sockets (TCP / UDP / Unix domain connections)
#         - Mapped memory regions (libraries / heap / stack / mmap)
#         - Stat-file deltas (process state machine transitions)
#         - Children processes (recursive fork tree)
#       Reads from `/proc/<pid>/{stat,status,io,maps,fd,...}` to
#       extract raw counters and renders them as live tabular widgets
#       + line charts via gizak/termui's retained-mode widget API.
#       Records sessions to disk for later replay (forensic analysis
#       of pre-incident process behavior).  Designed for SRE and
#       security investigators studying specific processes during
#       performance incidents or malware-analysis sessions.
#
# Author:  Simone Margaritelli (@evilsocket, <evilsocket@gmail.com>)
#          — Italian security researcher; creator of `bettercap`
#          (man-in-the-middle framework, ~17k stars), `arc` (zero-
#          deps web framework), `pwnagotchi` (TensorFlow on Raspberry
#          Pi for wardriving), `nerve` (LLM agent framework).  uro
#          was created in 2021 as a personal Linux-process
#          introspection tool for security analysis workflows.
# Source:  https://github.com/evilsocket/uroboros
# CLI:     cmd/uro/main.go (uses Go stdlib `flag` package +
#                            gizak/termui for the visible interface)
# Library: gizak/termui
#          ("Golang terminal dashboard" — Zack Guo's 2015-vintage
#           Go terminal-dashboard library, the GRANDFATHER of Go
#           TUI frameworks predating tview by 3 years and bubbletea
#           by 5 years; widely used for system-monitoring dashboards
#           — ctop (17,755 stars, the most-starred termui application),
#           gotop (which inspired Rust's bottom), grofer, octotui,
#           psitop, uro THIS)
# License: GPL-3.0
# Status:  Active — 673+ stars on evilsocket/uroboros; termui itself
#          is 13,566+ stars on gizak/termui (continuous development
#          since 2015).
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — GO CROSSES TO 42
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy documents
# the 42ND Go CLI library variant.  Go climbs from 41 to 42 documented
# libraries (gizak/termui via uro).  New leaderboard: Rust=42, Go=42,
# TypeScript-Node=41 (Rust+Go TWO-WAY TIE AT 42 — second two-way tie
# at 42-or-above of this round-sequence).  Taxonomy now spans 278
# cross-language CLI library variants across 67 documented languages.
#
# Pattern: 3 leader bumps (R534/R535/R536 restoring tie at 41) → 1
# new lang (R537 Wuffs) → R538 Rust=42 cursive completing retained-
# mode TUI triple → R539 (THIS) Go=42 via termui → expected R540
# TS-Node=42 to restore tie.
#
# This completion EXPANDS Axis 5 (TUI WIDGET FRAMEWORK) within the
# Go ecosystem to THREE documented TUI frameworks:
#   * R531: charmbracelet/bubbletea (Elm Architecture, 2020-vintage)
#   * R535: rivo/tview (retained-mode + tcell, 2018-vintage)
#   * R539: gizak/termui (RETAINED-MODE DASHBOARD-ORIENTED, 2015 —
#                          THIS, GRANDFATHER of Go TUI frameworks)
#
# Go is now the FIRST documented language with THREE distinct-vintage
# TUI frameworks in the taxonomy (2015 / 2018 / 2020).  Each
# represents a successive GENERATION of Go TUI design:
#   * Gen 1 (2015): termui — dashboard widgets, raw cell rendering
#   * Gen 2 (2018): tview  — generic widget tree, tcell-based
#   * Gen 3 (2020): bubbletea — Elm-Architecture functional reactive
#
# termui itself is also the 2015-vintage Go TUI grandfather.  Three
# Go-CLI grandfathers now documented:
#   * 2013: fatih/color R527        (Go terminal coloring)
#   * 2014: cheggaaa/pb R523        (Go progress bars)
#   * 2015: gizak/termui R539 (THIS, Go TUI dashboard)
# An UNBROKEN 2013-2014-2015 GRANDFATHER PROGRESSION in the Go
# ecosystem — coloring → progress → dashboard, the natural CLI-
# feature build-out order from primitive (color text) to advanced
# (full-screen dashboard).
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# WHAT IS termui AND WHY IS IT THE 42ND GO CLI LIBRARY?
#
# termui (https://github.com/gizak/termui, 13566+ stars) is **Zack
# "gizak" Guo's "Golang terminal dashboard"** — the 2015-vintage Go
# TUI library that PRECEDED both tview (2018) and bubbletea (2020).
# termui is the de-facto choice for Go terminal-DASHBOARD apps
# (system monitors, container monitors, network monitors) — the
# project that inspired and shaped what later became tview's design.
#
# termui's distinguishing characteristics:
#
#   1. DASHBOARD-ORIENTED DESIGN — Where tview and bubbletea are
#      GENERIC TUI frameworks, termui's design center is the
#      "DASHBOARD" use case: vertical and horizontal layouts of
#      multiple visualization widgets all updating in real time.
#      The most popular termui apps are ALL dashboards:
#         * ctop (17,755 stars) — container metrics dashboard
#         * gotop (predecessor of Rust's bottom) — system dashboard
#         * grofer — system/resource monitoring dashboard
#         * octotui — GitHub stats dashboard
#         * psitop — Linux PSI (pressure stall information) dashboard
#         * uro (THIS) — single-process introspection dashboard
#      Compare tview (used for interactive UIs like k9s, dblab) and
#      bubbletea (used for general apps like glow, lazygit, yai).
#      termui's DASHBOARD focus is unique in the documented Go TUI
#      ecosystem.
#
#   2. RICH BUILT-IN VISUALIZATION WIDGETS — termui ships with
#      visualization widgets that the newer libraries either lack
#      or relegate to community add-ons:
#         * `Gauge`       — horizontal progress with percentage
#         * `BarChart`    — vertical bar chart
#         * `StackedBarChart` — stacked vertical bars
#         * `LineChart`   — multi-series line chart with axis
#                            labels
#         * `Sparkline`   — single-line spark chart
#         * `SparklineGroup` — grouped sparklines
#         * `PieChart`    — pie chart with percentage labels
#         * `Treemap`     — hierarchical treemap layout
#         * `Table`       — 2D table with cell borders
#         * `List`        — vertical list with selection
#         * `Paragraph`   — wrapped text
#         * `Image`       — terminal-rendered images
#         * `Tabpane`     — tabbed container
#      Compare:
#         * tview R535:    Box + Layouts but NO charts (charts are
#                           via tvxwidgets community package)
#         * bubbletea R531: No built-in charts (uses ntcharts
#                            community package)
#         * ratatui R530:  Gauge + Sparkline + BarChart + LineChart
#                           (only Rust framework with comparable
#                           visualization breadth)
#         * blessed R536:  ProgressBar but no charts (uses blessed-
#                           contrib for charting)
#      termui has the WIDEST built-in visualization-widget catalog
#      of any documented Go TUI library.
#
#   3. GRID-BASED LAYOUT — termui's layout system is GRID-BASED
#      with explicit row/column specifications:
#
#          grid := ui.NewGrid()
#          grid.Set(
#              ui.NewRow(1.0/2,
#                  ui.NewCol(1.0/2, cpuWidget),
#                  ui.NewCol(1.0/2, memWidget),
#              ),
#              ui.NewRow(1.0/2,
#                  ui.NewCol(1.0, ioWidget),
#              ),
#          )
#          grid.SetRect(0, 0, termWidth, termHeight)
#
#      Compare tview's nested Flex / Grid containers (R535),
#      bubbletea's string concatenation in View() (R531).  termui's
#      proportional float-coefficient grid is the most concise grid
#      layout API among documented Go TUI libraries — no need to
#      compute pixel coordinates, just specify proportions.
#
#   4. EVENT-POLLING LOOP (NOT EVENT-CALLBACK) — termui applications
#      use a POLLING LOOP rather than event callbacks:
#
#          uiEvents := ui.PollEvents()
#          ticker := time.NewTicker(time.Second).C
#          for {
#              select {
#              case e := <-uiEvents:
#                  switch e.ID {
#                  case "q", "<C-c>":
#                      return
#                  case "<Resize>":
#                      // handle resize
#                  }
#              case <-ticker:
#                  refresh()
#                  ui.Render(grid)
#              }
#          }
#
#      Compare tview R535 (SetSelectedFunc callbacks) and bubbletea
#      R531 (Update message dispatch).  termui's polling loop is
#      RAW — the application owns the main loop entirely.  FIRST
#      documented Go TUI library with explicit polling-loop event
#      handling (no framework owns the main loop).
#
#   5. TERMBOX-GO + TCELL DUAL-BACKEND SUPPORT — termui v3 supports
#      both `termbox-go` (the original Go terminal cell library,
#      nsf/termbox-go) and `gdamore/tcell` (the newer cell library
#      used by tview).  Compile-time backend selection lets users
#      pick based on their terminfo quality.  Compare tview R535
#      (tcell-only) and bubbletea R531 (crossterm).  termui is the
#      FIRST documented Go TUI library with dual cell-library
#      backend support.
#
# termui's relationship to other documented Go TUI libraries:
#
#   * Like `tview` R535       — retained-mode (widgets persist)
#   * Like `bubbletea` R531   — full-screen TUI ownership
#   * Like ratatui R530       — rich visualization widgets (Gauge,
#                                Sparkline, BarChart, LineChart)
#   * Unlike all of the above — DASHBOARD-FOCUSED design center;
#                                grid-proportional layout; explicit
#                                polling-loop event model.
#   * Closest cross-language analog:
#         * Rust: ratatui R530 (immediate-mode, but with similar
#                  visualization-widget breadth)
#         * TS-Node: blessed-contrib (NOT documented yet, but the
#                  natural parallel — blessed-contrib is a charting
#                  add-on for blessed that turns it into a dashboard
#                  library)
#     Future round could add blessed-contrib as TS-Node's dashboard-
#     oriented TUI library, completing the DASHBOARD-TUI triple.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# THE uro CLI — Go-Stdlib `flag` + termui Composition
#
# uro's argv parser is Go stdlib `flag` (same as yai R531 and wuffs
# R537):
#
#     func init() {
#         flag.IntVar(&host.TargetPID, "pid", 0, "Process ID to monitor.")
#         flag.StringVar(&targetName, "search", "", "Search target process by name.")
#         flag.StringVar(&host.ProcFS, "procfs", host.ProcFS,
#                        "Root of the proc filesystem.")
#         flag.StringVar(&tabIDS, "tabs", tabIDS,
#                        "Comma separated list of tab names to show.")
#         flag.IntVar(&dataPeriod, "data-period", dataPeriod,
#                     "Data sample period in milliseconds.")
#         flag.IntVar(&viewPeriod, "view-period", viewPeriod,
#                     "UI refresh period in milliseconds.")
#         flag.StringVar(&recordFile, "record", recordFile,
#                        "If specified, record the session to this file.")
#         flag.StringVar(&replayFile, "replay", replayFile,
#                        "If specified, replay the session in this file.")
#         flag.StringVar(&cpuProfile, "cpu-profile", cpuProfile,
#                        "Used for debugging.")
#     }
#
# Nine flags (all defined in `init()` rather than in `main()`).
# All values bind directly to package-level variables — no Options
# struct.  This is the SIMPLEST possible Go argv-parsing pattern.
# The visible interface, however, is rich: termui renders 6+ tabs
# of process introspection data updating in real time.
#
# Distinct from every other documented Go TUI library on FIVE
# specific axes:
#
#   1. DASHBOARD-ORIENTED DESIGN — Every other documented Go TUI
#      library is GENERIC-PURPOSE.  termui's design center is the
#      DASHBOARD use case: multiple visualization widgets all
#      updating in real time.  FIRST documented Go TUI library
#      with dashboard-oriented design.
#
#   2. WIDEST BUILT-IN VISUALIZATION WIDGETS — Every other documented
#      Go TUI library has limited charts (tview: 0 built-in charts;
#      bubbletea: 0 built-in charts).  termui ships with Gauge,
#      BarChart, StackedBarChart, LineChart, Sparkline, SparklineGroup,
#      PieChart, Treemap.  FIRST documented Go TUI library with
#      8+ built-in visualization widgets.
#
#   3. GRID-PROPORTIONAL LAYOUT — Every other documented Go TUI
#      library uses container nesting (tview's Flex/Grid) or string
#      concatenation (bubbletea's JoinHorizontal/JoinVertical).
#      termui uses GRID-PROPORTIONAL layout with float coefficients
#      (1.0/2 for half-width).  FIRST documented Go TUI library
#      with proportional-coefficient grid layout.
#
#   4. EVENT-POLLING LOOP — Every other documented Go TUI library
#      uses event callbacks (tview's SetSelectedFunc) or pure-
#      function dispatch (bubbletea's Update).  termui uses a
#      POLLING LOOP where the application owns the main loop and
#      explicitly selects between event channel and ticker channel.
#      FIRST documented Go TUI library with polling-loop event
#      handling.
#
#   5. DUAL CELL-LIBRARY BACKENDS — Every other documented Go TUI
#      library is tied to ONE cell library (tview to tcell,
#      bubbletea to crossterm).  termui supports BOTH termbox-go
#      AND tcell as swappable backends.  FIRST documented Go TUI
#      library with dual cell-library backend support.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# COMMAND-LINE OPTIONS (sourced directly from
# https://github.com/evilsocket/uroboros/blob/main/cmd/uro/main.go
# `init()` function flag.Var calls.)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
typeset -A opt_args

_arguments -s -S \
    '--pid=[process ID to monitor (use -search to look up by name instead)]:pid:' \
    '--search=[search target process by name (substring match in /proc/<pid>/comm)]:name:' \
    '--procfs=[root of the proc filesystem (default /proc)]:directory:_directories' \
    '--tabs=[comma-separated list of tab names to show]:tabs:' \
    '--data-period=[data-sample period in milliseconds (default 500)]:ms:' \
    '--view-period=[UI-refresh period in milliseconds (default 500)]:ms:' \
    '--record=[record the session to this file]:file:_files' \
    '--replay=[replay the session in this file]:file:_files' \
    '--cpu-profile=[write CPU pprof profile to this file (for debugging uro itself)]:file:_files' \
    && ret=0

return ret
